Keep your curves, make glute gains, all while being cruelty free and saving money! #veganwithcurves #vegangains #glutegainz #veganweightgain #thickveganchick #curvyvegan #blackvegans #tiktokvegans 

Happy Sunday! Working on this Budget Friendly Vegan Weight Gain Video! I decided to do a series with multiple stores (Walmart, Aldi, and Trader Joes) but we gonna first start with Walmart since it got the most votes. Make sure y'all are subscribed to my YouTube channel!

In the meantime, lets talk about a few weight gain myths. 

🛑Myth: Working out glutes more makes them grow faster.

✅️Fact: Glutes (and every other muscle) grows when you REST it..NOT when your breaking down in the gym.

🛑Myth: Carbs are not important for glute gains.

✅️Fact: Eating too little carbs can lead to glycogen stores being depleted causing your body to breaking down protein for fuel which is needed to help build muscle. So if you want glutes..carb tf up!

🛑Myth: You can't build glutes as a vegan

✅️Fact: You build muscle on any diet as long as you have the right amout of calories, macro nutrients, and consistency in lifting weights.

Comment on my YouTube Video

"Curves come with DNA. Love you both inside and out. The cover photo for this video (was me showing my curves) should of been food pics! Just saying"

Well l make my YouTube cover photos of food when it's a recipe. I'm sitting in front of the camera talking about curves so why does the cover needs to be of food instead of me? 

But lets address this DNA thing. When I gain weight, MY DNA writes that the weight goes to my hips, butt, thighs, and STOMACH.

In the first pic  I was around 155 -165 lbs. I was not working out. The weight I gain was excess fat. So I carried A LOT of weight around my midsection as well as my butt, hips, and thighs. 

In the second pic I lost all that weight. I weighed around 98 - 100 lbs. I was still not working out so I didnt retain any "curves" on my body. 

Now I fluctuate between 142-148 lbs. I STILL gain weight in my stomach BUT because I am breaking down muscle, the weight around my midsection is not as much. It's there; I dont have abs as you can see nor do I want any (never cared about having visible abs 🤷🏾‍♀️). But the weight I gain was more muscle than fat. This is called body recomposition. Tho my DNA saids "weight gain in stomach", I "edited" to say "not so much"  by building muscle. 

So when I say curves, I AM TALKING ABOUT MUSCLE. MUSCLE = CURVES. I say this over and over again.  Also I am HUGE promoter of being the curvy version of YOU! Appreciate YOUR natural body and natural curves

Ladies, build your glutes around your cycle

Menstrual Phase: Low impact workouts like light yoga, walking, mobility and stretching workouts...or nothing at all if you are not feeling up to it.

Follicular Phase (right after cycle): Your energy rises again so this great for your normal routine of weights and if you need to burn fat while building muscle, HIIT Cardio workouts as well.

Ovulation Phase: You have the most energy here and are ready to go!  This phase might have you making calls to your no good ex 🥴but no hunney lol. Burn off that extra energy gym! It's peak time for building muscle and burning fat.

Luteal Phase: The first half of this phase you will have high energy but then it will start to dip a little as you are going into your next cycle. So for the first half, continue your heavy weight lifting (low impac cardio as you want to save all that energy for weights), but as you get close to your cycle, listen to your body and go lighter and less intense with your workouts. I usually drop the amount of weight I am lifting during the 2nd half of this phase or do body weight resistence only.

The top is before. The bottom is now. Natural glute growth is possible. Your glutes are a muscle. You break it down and build it back up stronget and bigger.

Yes it takes time but is more than possible. And no surgery is not a "quick" route. Surgery requires a lot of recovery time on top you still have to workout to keep it up. Otherwise gravity will take effect and you will begin to look disproportionate.

People that say "you always had that" didn't know me in these before pics. Clearly that was not the case. I am a vegan so I gain healthy weight on a plant based diet. 

Important key tips to remember

✅️ Eat in a surplus of calories daily. This means whatever your maintence calories are, you will want to eat anywhere 300 to 500 calories more above that daily. You will want to monitor this to make sure you are making gains, or to make sure you are not gaining too fast (excess fat instead of muscle)

✅️Glutes grow when you REST..NOT when you're breaking them down in the gym. So do not work them more than 2-3 times a week.

✅️Eating too little carbs can lead to glycogen stores being depleted causing your body to break down protein for fuel which is needed to help build glute muscle. So if you want glutes..carb tf up! 

✅️You need plant based protein (amino acids)! Aim for 0.7 to 1 gram of protein in grams per body weight in pounds. For instance if you weigh 100 lbs, you would aim for anywhere between 70 -100 grams of protein daily.

✅️Make sure you have good stomach acid (hydrochloric acid)to break down your food especially protein based foods. Fermented foods can help with restoring a proper gut chemistry.

✅️ Not training your upper body will cause muscle imbalances. Plus it is hard to progressively overload in things like squats or RDLs (important compound movements) if you can't even lift the weight due to a weak upper body. 

✅️Please love yourself and your body. Stop comparing yourself to unrealistic body standards. Stop comparing your shape to someone else. 

Last but not least STAY CONSISTENT!!!!!💪🏿

Dear Vegans, you do NOT have to downplay protein!

 I'm an outlier in a Vegan Community because I'm one of the rare vegans that actually appreciates having a higher intake of plant-based protein. While I do agree that there isn't anything to worry about regarding protein deficiency as long as you're eating enough calories, sometimes I think vegans downplay it too much.

This is anecdote evidence but for me, I feel the most satiated when my diet is slightly higher in fats and protein. Beyond my anecdotal proof,  it has been shown that adequate protein intake  helps maintain a healthy bone mass. Besides if you want to build curves you need to prioritize weightlifting and protein.

You can be vegan and love protein too!💪🏿😁#veganwithcurves #vegansloveproteintoo #veganprotein #plantbasedprotein

People often tell me I don't look vegan because of how I carry my weight. Well that's because I EAT! I workout too but I eat enough food from all 3 macro groups (carbs, protein, and fat). 

And I live off of more than just watermelon.  Y'all going to "heal" yourself until you're malnourished if you don't cut it out. Brittle nails and hair falling out is probably NOT a sign of detoxing. More than likely it's a sign you're missing some healthy fats and/or important amino acids. Stop with these extreme vegan diets.🚫🙅🏾‍♀️

My Top Glute Exercises (In no particular order)

✅️KAS Glute Bridge (pause at the top for 3 secs)
✅️Hip Thrust (pause at the top for 3 secs
✅️Hack/V Squat
✅️Split Squat (The Devil🥺🥴)
✅️Deficit Reverse Lunge (The Devil's Child lol)
✅️Glute Focus Back Extension
✅️Glute/Donkey Kickback
✅️ Romanian Deadlift
✅️ Conventional Deadlift
✅️Leg Press

To grow your glutes as a vegan, you need to eat enough plant based protein...between 0.8 and 1 g of protein per pound of body weight. Eat enough calories overall; slight surplus in a bulking phase. Most important...HAVE REST DAYS. Please please do not work out your glutes more than 2 to 3 times a week. (I prefer only 2x a week)
